:"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1250–":"circa 1250–Overleden","1271–Female":"1271–Overleden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","about 1250":"circa 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1271–Female":"1271–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","about 1250":"about 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Purcell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Old French <i>pourcel</i> ‘little pig’ (from Latin <i>porcellus</i>, a diminutive of <i>porcus</i> ‘pig’), hence a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd, or a nickname, perhaps denoting someone thought to resemble a pig. This surname is common in Ireland, having become established there in the 12th century. There may sometimes be confusion with   Pearsall  .","English: habitational name from Purshull in Elmbridge, Worcestershire. The placename derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pearsall","meanings":["English (West Midlands):","habitational name from Pearshall in Staffordshire. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>pise</i>, <i>peosu</i> ‘pea’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’.","occasionally a variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parcells","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Purcell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Parcel","meanings":["English (Surrey) and Welsh (Glamorgan): variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parsell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Parsells","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Persell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Procell","meanings":["Probably an altered (metathesized) form of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Pursell","meanings":["English: variant of   Purcell  .","Americanized form of German <b>Burschel</b> or <b>Bürschel</b>, diminutives of   Bursch  ."]},{"name":"Parcell","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Purcell  ."]},{"name":"Percell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Purcell  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Purcell was born about 1250, in Merton, Devon, England. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"fi":{"about 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1271–Female":"1271–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England"},"fr":{"about 1250–":"environ 1250–Décédé","1271–Female":"1271–Décédée","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","about 1250":"environ 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Purcell est né environ 1250, à Merton, Devon, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1250–":"um 1250–Verstorben","1271–Female":"1271–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","about 1250":"um 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon, England":"Merton, Devon, England","lifeSummary":"William Purcell wurde um 1250 in Merton, Devon, England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"about 1250–":"about 1250–Desede","1271–Female":"1271–Desede","1250–Male":"1250–Desede","about 1250":"about 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Merton, Devon,